-- BP, Daily Mail, Domino's, HSBC, ITV May Move: U.K., Irish Equity Preview
-- Sarah Jones
-- 2010-07-12T06:49:37Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-11/bp-british-airways-hsbc-interserve-plc-itv-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in U.K. and Irish
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the last market close.  
 The benchmark  FTSE 100 Index  climbed 27.49, or 0.5 percent,
to 5,132.94. The  FTSE All-Share Index  rose 0.5 percent and
Ireland’s  ISEQ Index  retreated 0.4 percent.  
 BP Plc  (BP/ LN): The energy company is in talks to sell
assets to Apache Corp. as it seeks funds to pay for the biggest
U.S. oil spill in history, two people familiar with the
discussions said. Apache is negotiating for assets that include
a share in BP’s Alaska business, for a price of less than $12
billion, according to one of the people, who asked not to be
identified because the discussions aren’t public. The shares
lost 0.6 percent to 364.8 pence.  
 British Airways Plc  (BAY LN): Europe’s third-largest
carrier will try to grow in Madrid’s Barajas airport after a
merger with Iberia Lineas Aereas de Espana SA if it can’t
continue to expand in London’s Heathrow, El Pais reported,
citing Chief Executive Officer  Willie Walsh . The shares rose 0.6
percent to 206.7 pence.  
 Daily Mail & General Trust Plc  (DMGT LN): The publisher of
the Daily Mail newspaper is looking to trade its Northcliffe
newspaper unit to either  Johnston Press Plc  (JPR LN) or  Trinity
Mirror Plc  (TNI LN), the Sunday Times said. Daily Mail shares
rose 0.8 percent to 461.1 pence.  
 Domino’s Pizza U.K. & Ireland Plc  (DOM LN): Britain’s
largest pizza-delivery chain reported a 29 percent rise in
first-half pretax profit to 17.5 million pounds ($26 million).
The shares advanced 0.9 percent to 403 pence.  
 HSBC Holdings Plc  (HSBA LN): Morgan Stanley’s
infrastructure unit,  3i Infrastructure Plc  (3IN LN) and Star
Capital are close to buying U.K. train rolling-stock leasing
operations owned by HSBC for about 1.7 billion pounds, the
Sunday Times said, citing people with knowledge of the talks.
HSBC rose 0.6 percent to 627.1 pence.  
 Interserve Plc  (IRV LN): The company that maintains the
British Army’s training grounds said sales from public-sector
clients may drop 5 percent to 10 percent in the next two years
as the U.K. government reins in spending. The shares fell 0.3
percent to 201.5 pence.  
 ITV Plc  (ITV LN): The U.K.’s biggest commercial broadcaster
exceeded analysts’ forecasts in June by boosting advertising
revenue 45 percent on its flagship channel, ITV1, because of the
World Cup, the Financial Times reported. The stock rose 2.5
percent to 52.05 pence.  
 Kier Group Plc  (KIE LN): The U.K. company that helped build
the Channel Tunnel said full-year pretax profit will be toward
the upper end of the current range of analyst estimates. The
shares fell 0.9 percent to 943 pence.  
 Petrofac Plc  (PFC LN): The oilfield services and
engineering company said it was awarded a production enhancement
services contract by OMV Petrom SA in Romania. The shares fell
0.8 percent to 1,236 pence.  
 Thomas Cook Group Plc  (TCG LN): Europe’s second-largest
travel company agreed to buy Oger Tours GmbH, which sells
holidays in Turkey, for about 30 million euros ($38 million).
The shares rose 1.3 percent to 191.5 pence.  
